# Manual Checklist Maintenance Rule

The manual test checklist lives in `dev/check/` as **one Markdown file per section**
(e.g. `dev/check/BOARD.md`, `dev/check/PGNEDIT.md`).
`dev/check/00_README.md` is the index with a table pointing to every section file.

Each section file has three parts:
1. A YAML-like frontmatter block (`section:`, `area:`).
2. A `## Key source files` block listing the implementation files most relevant to
   that section (relative paths from repo root, one bullet per file with a short note).
3. A `## Checklist` block containing the test items.

## When to update

Update the relevant section file(s) **in the same session** as any change that
introduces, alters, or removes something a user can observe or interact with:

| Trigger | Examples |
|---|---|
| New feature | New dialog, new toolbar button, new panel, new import method |
| Changed behaviour | Renamed button, altered workflow, new keyboard shortcut |
| Removed feature | Panel removed, mode dropped, shortcut changed |
| Bug fix that changes observable behaviour | Fix for a crash, silent failure, or wrong result |
| New plan phase completed | Any phase in a `dev/plans/*.plan.md` that ships UI |

Do **not** update for: pure refactoring, type changes, test additions, internal
module splits, or performance work with no visible effect.

## Required actions when updating

1. **Identify the right section file(s)** — use the index in `dev/check/00_README.md`.
   If no section fits, create a new `dev/check/NEWSECTION.md` and add a row to the index.
2. **Add new items** for every new testable behaviour (append at end of `## Checklist`).
3. **Update existing items** if a behaviour changed (do not leave stale descriptions).
4. **Remove items** for features that were deleted entirely.
5. **Update the `## Key source files` block** if new implementation files were added or
   renamed as part of the change.
6. **Reset any `[x]` to `[ ]`** for items whose behaviour changed — they need re-verification.

There is no "Last updated" date to maintain — git history is the record of changes.

## When the user asks you to "check my checks"

Read **every section file** in `dev/check/` (not just the index).
For each file, fully reconcile the `## Checklist` and `## Key source files` blocks
against the current codebase:
- Verify that referenced source paths still exist; update or remove stale ones.
- Add source paths for implementation files you find that are relevant but missing.
- Add, update, or remove checklist items to match the current observable behaviour.
- Reset `[x]` items that are stale due to recent changes.

Write all updates back to the section files before reporting done.

## Item format

```
- [ ] **SECTION-N** — One sentence describing exactly what to do and what to expect.
```

- The ID (`SECTION-N`) must be unique across the entire `dev/check/` directory.
- The description must be concrete enough that the user can reference it by ID
  (e.g. "WEBIMPORT-3 doesn't work") and you will immediately know what it refers to.
- Use imperative or declarative phrasing focused on the observable result:
  *"Paste `https://lichess.org/<id>` opens the full game PGN."*
  Not: *"Test Lichess import."*

## Status symbols

| Symbol | Meaning |
|--------|---------|
| `[ ]` | Not yet tested |
| `[x]` | Verified passing |
| `[!]` | Bug found by user — needs fixing |
| `[~]` | Fix applied by Claude — awaiting user recheck |

When the user marks an item `[!]`, they add an indented `> ` observation line:

```
- [!] **BOARD-3** — Pawn promotion: a picker appears; selecting a piece completes the promotion.
  > The picker never appears — pawn auto-promotes to queen.
```

When fixing `[!]` items:
1. Read all `[!]` items and their `> ` notes across all section files.
2. Investigate and fix each one.
3. Change `[!]` to `[~]` and remove the `> ` note.
4. Do **not** change to `[x]` — the user must recheck before marking verified.

## Numbering

- Within each section, number items sequentially: `SECTION-1`, `SECTION-2`, etc.
- When inserting a new item mid-section, append at the end — do not renumber
  existing items (the user may have recorded failures against old IDs).

